The paper uses deep learning-based visual analysis to estimate person-specific behavior parameters, which suggests that it belongs to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper utilizes game theory to model the interdependent decision-making process of multiple pedestrians, which suggests that it belongs to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of classifiers and predictive models, which are common in the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper deals with multi-pedestrian interactions, which suggests that it may belong to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with predicting pedestrian behavior, which suggests that it may belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category.
